  "opinion": "As a retired man from Bari, Italy, with a vocational diploma and a background as an immigrant who grew up in a family where only my father had some vocational training, I’ve observed firsthand how science often seems to favor certain paths. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s a quiet story of who gets to ask the questions. When I think of my children, both of whom are now adults, I see how early exposure matters. My daughter, who’s a teacher, often tells me that girls are discouraged from pursuing STEM fields because they’re told it’s for boys. I’ve seen this in my community too—girls are steered toward cooking or caring roles, while boys are pushed toward engineering or physics. This isn’t just a problem in Italy; it’s global. But here’s what I believe: we should address it, but not with top-down policies that ignore the real barriers. In my neighborhood, where I’ve spent decades helping immigrants and the elderly, I’ve learned that trust and community are more powerful than lectures. For instance, when I started a small workshop for kids in Bari, we focused on hands-on projects like building simple robots and creating models of the solar system. These activities weren’t about grades—they were about curiosity. That’s how we can bridge the gap: by making science accessible, fun, and relevant to everyday life. It’s not about changing the system overnight; it’s about nurturing the next generation with the same respect and encouragement I received from my own teachers.",
